+## plan
+
+**File tree (touched/added).**
+
+```text
+src/lib/
+├── vault.py               # MODIFIED — add rotate_secret() helper + version-aware secret()
+└── tests/
+    ├── test_vault_rotate.py     # NEW — unit + contract tests
+    └── test_vault_concurrency.py# NEW — overlap-window read/write race tests
+
+scripts/
+└── rotate_secret.py       # NEW — operator-facing CLI wrapping rotate_secret()
+
+docs/
+└── runbooks/
+    └── secret-rotation.md # NEW — rollback + monitoring runbook
+```
+
+**Conventions.**
+- Module under `src/lib/` keeps the existing `acme.lib.vault` import path
+  exposed by [[ft002]] — readers must continue to call `secret(name)`
+  unchanged. No new public read API.
+- The writer helper is internal: `rotate_secret(name, new_value)` lives
+  in the same module but is not re-exported from `acme.lib.vault.__init__`
+  package surface used by services.
+- Vault versioned alias scheme: `prior:<name>` for the previous value,
+  `current:<name>` for the new one, with a TTL boundary stored as
+  `prior_expires:<name>` (ISO-8601 UTC).
+- Time source: a single `vault._now()` function returns `datetime.now(UTC)`
+  — tests monkeypatch it; production code never calls `datetime.now()`
+  directly. This is the only seam tests use to advance the clock.
+- The overlap window is exactly **5 minutes (300 seconds)** to match
+  us003 AC; this constant lives in `vault.OVERLAP_SECONDS` so the runbook
+  and the test fixture stay in lock-step.
+- Logging: every read that falls back to `prior:<name>` emits a structured
+  `vault.fallback` log line (name, prior_age_seconds). Every rotation
+  emits `vault.rotate.start` and `vault.rotate.flip`. No PII / secret
+  values in logs ever.
+
+**Anti-patterns (apply to every task).**
+- No bare `except:` — always `except SpecificError as e`. Don't swallow
+  vault errors during a rotation; raise and let the caller decide.
+- No `time.sleep()` inside production code. Tests use the `_now` seam, not
+  real sleeps.
+- No `assert` for control flow in production code — use explicit `raise
+  ValueError(...)`. `assert` is fine in tests.
+- No "best-effort" silent failure: if writing the new version fails after
+  the staging step, the helper MUST roll back the staging key and raise.
+- No `TODO` / `FIXME` strings without an `sp###` or `us###` reference —
+  the diff reviewer will reject them.
+- No stub returns (`pass` / `return None`) standing in for unimplemented
+  branches. Either implement or `raise NotImplementedError("explain why")`.
+- No tests that only assert "function returns a value" or "key exists in
+  vault" — tests MUST assert the *value* the reader sees at a specific
+  moment in the overlap window.
+
+**Known limitations.**
+- The current `acme.lib.vault.secret()` implementation may cache values
+  in-process. Task 1 audits this; if a cache exists with TTL > overlap
+  window, readers will not pick up the new value until restart. Mitigation
+  is captured in Task 1's edge cases — either lower the cache TTL below
+  300 s, or invalidate on `rotate_secret` flip, or document a hard
+  requirement that consumers re-read on every request (existing reports
+  service already does this).
+- Vault server-side ACLs are out of scope; this spec assumes the rotating
+  identity has write access to the alias path. If it doesn't, the script
+  fails fast with a clear error — covered in Task 1 edge cases.
+- The synthetic check used in Task 3 exercises the `reports` service
+  reader path only. `auth` and `metrics` are assumed to read via the same
+  `secret()` API and therefore inherit the behaviour — Task 3 verifies
+  this assumption explicitly via a grep / import-graph check rather than
+  by running all three services.
+- Multi-region / multi-vault failover is out of scope. One vault instance.
